## `Tools/ApiTools.cs`

```csharp
using ModelContextProtocol.Server;
using System.ComponentModel;
using System.Text.Json;

[McpServerToolType]
public class ApiTools(HttpClient httpClient, ILogger<ApiTools> logger)
{
    [McpServerTool, Description("Retrieve a user by their unique ID.")]
    public async Task<string> GetUser(
        [Description("The numeric user ID")] int userId,
        CancellationToken cancellationToken = default)
    {
        logger.LogInformation("Fetching user {UserId}", userId);
        var response = await httpClient.GetAsync($"/users/{userId}", cancellationToken);
        response.EnsureSuccessStatusCode();
        return await response.Content.ReadAsStringAsync(cancellationToken);
    }

    [McpServerTool, Description("Search users by name. Returns matching results.")]
    public async Task<string> SearchUsers(
        [Description("Name or partial name to search for")] string query,
        [Description("Max results to return (1-50)")] int limit = 10,
        CancellationToken cancellationToken = default)
    {
        logger.LogInformation("Searching users: {Query}", query);
        var response = await httpClient.GetAsync(
            $"/users?name={Uri.EscapeDataString(query)}&limit={limit}", cancellationToken);
        response.EnsureSuccessStatusCode();
        return await response.Content.ReadAsStringAsync(cancellationToken);
    }

    [McpServerTool(ReadOnly = false), Description("Create a new user with the given name and email.")]
    public async Task<string> CreateUser(
        [Description("Full name of the user")] string name,
        [Description("Email address")] string email,
        CancellationToken cancellationToken = default)
    {
        var payload = JsonSerializer.Serialize(new { name, email });
        var content = new StringContent(payload, System.Text.Encoding.UTF8, "application/json");
        var response = await httpClient.PostAsync("/users", content, cancellationToken);
        response.EnsureSuccessStatusCode();
        return await response.Content.ReadAsStringAsync(cancellationToken);
    }
}
```

## `Program.cs` (stdio transport)

```csharp
using Microsoft.Extensions.DependencyInjection;
using Microsoft.Extensions.Hosting;
using Microsoft.Extensions.Logging;
using ModelContextProtocol.Server;

var builder = Host.CreateApplicationBuilder(args);

// CRITICAL: Log to stderr only — stdout is the JSON-RPC channel
builder.Logging.AddConsole(options =>
    options.LogToStandardErrorThreshold = LogLevel.Trace);

// Configure the HttpClient that gets injected into ApiTools
builder.Services.AddHttpClient<ApiTools>(client =>
{
    client.BaseAddress = new Uri("https://api.example.com");
    client.DefaultRequestHeaders.Add("Accept", "application/json");
});

builder.Services.AddMcpServer(options =>
{
    options.ServerInfo = new() { Name = "MyApiServer", Version = "1.0.0" };
})
.WithStdioServerTransport()
.WithToolsFromAssembly();   // discovers all [McpServerToolType] classes

await builder.Build().RunAsync();
```

---

## How DI Works for MCP Tools

The SDK supports two injection styles:

**1. Constructor injection (non-static class, shown above)**
`ApiTools` is a non-static class with a primary constructor. The DI container creates an instance per request, injecting `HttpClient` and `ILogger<ApiTools>` via the constructor. This is the preferred pattern when tools share services.

**2. Method parameter injection (static class)**
```csharp
[McpServerToolType]
public static class QuickTools
{
    [McpServerTool, Description("Ping the API.")]
    public static async Task<string> Ping(
        HttpClient httpClient,           // ← injected by DI, hidden from schema
        CancellationToken cancellationToken = default)
    {
        return await httpClient.GetStringAsync("/health", cancellationToken);
    }
}
```

**Key rule:** The SDK distinguishes tool parameters from injected services automatically. Types registered in DI (`HttpClient`, `ILogger<T>`, `IMcpServer`, `CancellationToken`, `IProgress<T>`) are resolved from the container and **never appear** in the tool's JSON schema that the LLM sees. Only parameters with `[Description]` are exposed to the LLM.
